Currently a valid digital storage system not available in all countries. Officially everything on paper (my personal opinion, we live in 2023 not 1923 ;) ). Time to go paperless. Biogen has underfunded data infrastructure for nearly 10 years and is about a decade behind most similar sized Biotechs in data capability. This is a massive threat to Biogen and is made even more visible since the massive personnel attrition which has highlighted that we did not institutionalize the tribal knowledge that has now left the company. So, not only is our data capability behind a decade, bu we have also lost a massive amount of tribal knowledge and true expertise by not being able to leverage that knowledge before it left Biogen. 
Biogen is at a turning point in its development and right now, it needs a massive investment in foundational capability and infrastructure. Stop focusing on the problems of today. Focus on the problems of the next ten years and ensure Biogen is investing to stay ahead rather than plug current holes.

Regarding data about Biogen's portfolio (thinking major metadata categories: program names, codes, clinical/commercial stage, modality, indication(s) administration routes, leadership, milestones/timelines) -- there is no centralized and encompassing ownership for data. I think that use of the Planisware Clarity system has been a positive step and I strongly support its continuation. However, there continue to be pockets of ownership, each with their own scope. For functions like mine, in which our org works on all project phases from pre-R2D through commercial and LCM, I am left having to manually combine information from the various ownership areas into order to get complete data sets to drive awareness and decision making. The separated info ownership also means that I have varying levels of confidence in data sources -- have to talk to many different owners - fill data gaps through informal paths. Ultimately, working with portfolio data takes massively more time and manual effort than I think it should at a company with our history and standing. Our data systems make it harder for me to do my job. I have a history of forming new partnerships and executing projects to solve these problems -- but, ultimately, this is outside of my job scope and consumes time that should go towards other work. The effort should be more universal.

Most Research data is maintained in Excel files rather than databases. This makes analysis of meta data impossible and makes the results from individual studies easy to lose. The ELN system is not easy to use.
Having a central search function/catalog will be very helpful

The FAIRness of data is very variable.  Accessing scientific literature through BLiNC: very good.  Using my own data through the ELN (Electronic Notebook): bad.  Using others' data through ELN:  bad.  Finding and accessing project team data outside my own:  Bad, because so many sites are locked by default.  Results from finding data through Synapse search: poor.

Getting information from other functional lines is exceptionally challenging. I worry about the veracity of the data from unupdated areas such as Clarity/OTL if these are being used to make decisions when there are all sorts of issues. It's about data and it's also about whether groups are shirking accountability- for example, they lose a person who knew how to do something- suddenly no one in the group knows how to do it so they decide to change the SOP to say that someone else is now responsible when that person also does not have access to training information or ability to correct, etc.

Currently, it is extremely difficult to access data generated by former research colleagues (or even those still here). ELN is not easily searchable, plus those are single experiments, not presentations of entire data sets/stories. It is difficult or impossible to find previous presentations unless you were in attendance and are on that specific Sharepoint. This results in people proposing avenues of research that may have already been investigated but have since been discontinued. It should be much easier to access most (if not all) internally generated data.
none

This survey seems very useful for taking stock of how Biogen uses its data to generate knowledge from it. At the moment, I expect Biogen's FAIR score to be rather low. I am curious to see what our 2022 FAIR score is and what actions we will take to improve it.
Research data are diverse and intricate, and I have no idea how they can be structured and managed in a manner that satisfies what is asked for by the data maturity definition.

The complete lack of centralization of data is ridiculous. Why are my reps sending me excel sheets of raw data instead of importing it into some easily accessible database that we can pull the data from in the future. It's bizarre that different line functions use different data bases and don't tell the other line functions how to use those databases (or that they even exist). We should have standardized data formats and hubs that we can conveniently and reliably access without needing specific point people to constantly direct the end user. It shouldn't take a year to get assay development to have a regular upload of data to biorails, it shouldn't take 2 months for DMPK reps to send out exposure data (in a PowerPoint too? every rep has a different format?!). Management needs to hold themselves accountable and realize that even if the department is happy with its own operations, that doesn't mean that subsequent users are happy. Getting data that is BUSINESS CRITICAL here is like pulling teeth.

Biogen is behind our competitors by a mile in this area, not sure we'll ever get there.  A fundamental culture change needs to happen, needs to be driven from the top to, not just say PTD or R&D or PO&T, and dont reinvent the wheel, there're already solutions out there.  Also, people are not even comfortable sharing a slide or data pack to edit or work up collectively, another culture issue that needs to change, everyone seems to hold their data or only store some of it on teams or whereever.  We need one electronic notebook (LIMS and scillegence ones are junk) and one place where all raw data and worked up data are stored.  On top of that, IT contractors are not connected with what is expected, our labs have devices storing data on local drives that only 1-2 people can log in to.  Too many people are storing information on their local drives and sharing by email.  Final reports are stored in myCIMS, however, finding the slidepacks and worked up data leading to those final reports is always difficult.  Almost every day I'm in a meeting where someone cannot locate the data, report, table, slidepack....
wewfwfwef

I believe Biogen is behind (5-10 years) the current state of art with managing data.  In addition, the culture is not 100% capable of using effectively the current systems we have which adds more complications to the problem.  This is something an external group can solve, but we shouldn't be designing the solution and solving the problem internally.

We are missing the technology to manage data effectively on on-prem shared storage. This is a specific problem for our HPC environment (even the new EDGE HPC) where either the HPC team or end-users can manage linking meta-data to files/folders. We lose the connection between who created, when they created it, and which project/sample the data is connected to. We need the technology to apply properties/tags to individual files (not folders) which remain linked and searchable (via API) in events such as archival, data migration (i.e. moving files/folders). Having one person (or team) to actively update a central database with data owner is not the answer.

It is great to see us putting effort and priority to improving data standards and processes on the commercial side.  I feel as though we have great foundational pieces from which we can continue to improve.
The ability to use and access data has become increasingly more difficult and there are fewer people who know how to access and use it.

It is too dependent on individuals. For example, when someone is out sick or on PTO, it's next to impossible to find anyone else who can pull the data or understands how. There are too many "single points of failure" possibilities.

There is a lack of respect from those who manage Veeva and those affected by the consequences of "Veeva Open Data". We are unwilling to flex our system to meet the needs of the business, stakeholders, and customers.

I'm from the Transparency so my responses were kind of a mix from the experience I had when I tried to find data from different systems, Veeva CRM, Veeva Vault, Veeva MDM, Oracle EBS. IT tickets were a life saver in general.
n/a

Being in the US organization and commercial data being so heavily used, I would argue that the organization needs to invest in the teams that are responsible to bring the data in to the broader organization.  We need more headcount to meet the needs and demands of the US org.
We have an opportunity to expand awareness, investment and expectations in all functions to build up data governance, and contribute to building the Global Data Platform with relevant use cases.

CCSLs should have access to eTMF where study data is archived. It is time comsuming asks CRO to provide study documents or even contact Sr CCSLs requesting those documents. It would be easier for our work if we have access to this data.

Q19: This initiative is great! Its what we need much more of to meet goals, live our internal vision and elements in our daily job execution.

It would be good to align on naming conventions across different documents, and different sites. e.g. the name of a given stage in manufacturing, or the name of a parameter. Without this, it is hard to combine data from different sources.

I would like to know what groups can support creation of data dashboards and create standards for such dashboards and data visualizations at Biogen.  A lot of times multiple groups collect the same data different ways and then have slightly different durations or values on the same things.

Data privacy is realy important, but there is no process at Biogen to evaluate on which roles need what type of data and when someone leaves Biogen is a big concern.  My team has received replies over e-mail that the data (filings, PDUFA, filings countries/regions, etc.  can't be shared bc is confidential, but without it we can lay out our strategy to support Biogen's partnerships.  There is also minimal investment in tools that can automate certain tasks, for which data/metadata could be use later for forecasts.  Even when Clarity is the source for CTs, the information (dates for major milestones) is normally dated or incomplete, and the program manager doesn't have the information.

Q10_70_TEXT: Primary Market Research & Competitive insight data - it is impossible to get Regional or Local data in most cases. Biogen needs to invest in data management infrastructure for CMI function, for democratized access to insight
Q19: Within Biogen we can do better to share access to provisioned data, in particular at Local and Regional levels, to support Global decision making. Likewise, investment in data management, consumption infrastructure for the CMI function would be helpful and put Biogen on par with competitors who have IT support systems for the function.

I am working with many different types of data. The stringency the data governance strategy varies with the type of data. For regulated data to be used in clinical trials, manufacturing and other regulated processes the quality management system is stringent and optimal. I have mostly problems to find interim or exploratory data that are managed by individual line functions. The way the data are managed are not always aligned between programs but the technical development team is currently working on harmonising this. The current survey primarily refers to these types of data.
I find that organizations create, manage and share data in silos. It is very difficult to navigate across Synapse, SharePoint, reporting tools, etc.

Need to improve onboarding process for new employees, or new members to the team, centralization of data governance, and set standards for the org, ie. all dashboards have a definition/glossary and main purpose/intent of dashboard,
